      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Shrinkage, the loss of inventory, is a real drain on your operational efficiency. To adjust your inventory turnover ratio for lost stock, you need to factor in the missing inventory as if it were sold or lost from your usable stock. A simple way to approach this is to adjust your Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) upwards to account for the value of the shrinkage. This will, in turn, increase your COGS, which will then lower your adjusted inventory turnover ratio, reflecting the true inventory movement.\n\nHere's the general formula:\n\n**Adjusted Inventory Turnover Ratio = (Beginning Inventory + Ending Inventory - Value of Shrinkage) / Average Inventory**\n\n*Wait, that formula is a bit complex for a quick fix, and the standard method is usually to adjust COGS.*\n\nLet's simplify the concept for you. You should calculate your standard Inventory Turnover Ratio first, and then increase your COGS by the dollar value of the shrinkage. Then, recalculate the ratio using that inflated COGS. This shows how much more \"inventory movement\" you are effectively experiencing due to the losses.\n\n**Standard Formula:**\n$$\\text{Inventory Turnover Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold (",
